{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/twitter-data-acquisition-and-pre-processing-using-r-c999746babbe", "time": 1683014962.856577, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/twitter-data-acquisition-and-pre-processing-using-r-c999746babbe/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Deep Tutorial for Twitter Data Acquisition and Pre-processing Using R | by Audhi Aprilliant | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Deep Tutorial for Twitter Data Acquisition and Pre-processing Using R", "description": "Using ggplot2 on R and Twitter data of Indonesia election 2019, it gets some insights about both of presidential candidate, Joko Widodo and Prabowo Subianto"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://github.com/audhiaprilliant/Indonesia-Public-Election-Twitter-Sentiment-Analysis", "anchor_text": "GitHub repo", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/twitter-data-visualization-fb4f45b63728", "anchor_text": "Twitter Data Visualization Using R", "paragraph_index": 18}, {"url": "http://audhiaprilliant.github.io/", "anchor_text": "http://audhiaprilliant.github.io/", "paragraph_index": 20}], "all_paragraphs": ["Twitter is social media that is used to spread information or opinion on a certain topic \u2014 can be a social or political phenomenon that happened in society. Twitter users can tweet their opinion using 280 characters, photos, voices, videos, links, etc.", "In my point of view, one of the most interesting elements of Twitter is a trending topic. It refers to a word or topic commonly discussed in a specific area and has the highest volume rather than others on the same date and time.", "This analysis was made during the Indonesia public election when campaign teams from the presidential candidate were doing a lot of political campaigns through social media, one of them being Twitter. It was like the online war of trending topics. Each team promoted their own presidential candidate and even used a black campaign. As a data scientist, that is like the treasure of data that can be analyzed, so we find out a pattern over the analysis. But, how do we get the Twitter data? And what is the next step? That will be covered in this story. Enjoy!", "Okay then, generally, the data can be easily taken by Twitter API and web scraping. The Twitter API can extract the data from our Twitter account \u2014 tweets in a certain date and time, number of followers & following of our account, etc.", "API stands for Application Programming Interface is a tool to connect the data between two application, formally in JSON format.", "This endpoint allows us to make a specific request, for instance, tweets from a certain time period and return it back to our application. In this case, R acts like the application. In order to begin using the Twitter API, we need a Twitter account that will get us access to an API Key (Consumer Key). So there are several steps to get Twitter API.", "Now, we will connect our application (R) with Twitter through API. Before we talk deeper about this, please make sure we have installed the twitterR and tm library in R.", "After the requirements are done, here we go to connect our application with Twitter using API.", "Using the function of searchTwitter, we can search any tweets for a certain time period, the number of tweets, and the language. You can find out any parameters on the docs. good to remember that there are a few rules to search for tweets using twitterR library.", "Finally, we reach out to the main topic of this story! But, before we conduct data pre-processing, we must know there are three main tasks in text pre-processing to do:", "To simplify our tasks, we would like to create an R file that contains some text pre-processing functions. So, we just need to call or import it when we need it in our main R file. To do so, create an R file named cleansing.R containing scripts below.", "Here we go! We will run the main script of R to conduct text pre-processing. Once again, this analysis is done in the Indonesian language. So, for the normalization and stopwords removal, it will be different from the English language, but we just need to adjust the data.", "First, we just conduct case-folding and filtering tasks. Let\u2019s go!", "After running the above script, we are easily able to see the differences between before and after the case-folding and filtering processes.", "Next, we meet at the checkpoint. Before doing text normalization and stopwords removal, we need to download two kinds of data as our lexicon:", "The last version of our data is as follows:", "Data pre-processing is a crucial and vital task in text mining. It determines the output of the whole analysis, like the GIGO (Garbage In Garbage Out). The social media data is too messy, so to make it more reliable for our analysis, the analyst must do the data pre-processing properly. Remember, there is no systematic order of pre-processing, the stopwords removal can be the first task to do, and also the process can be repeated depending on our needs.", "Please head over to my GitHub repo for looking at the completed codes.", "This story is related to the previous story of Twitter Data Visualization Using R. Let\u2019s code, analyze, and repeat!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Data Scientist. Tech Writer. Statistics, Data Analytics, and Computer Science Enthusiast. Portfolio & social media links at http://audhiaprilliant.github.io/"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fc999746babbe&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Ftwitter-data-acquisition-and-pre-processing-using-r-c999746babbe&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------",